<section xml:id="section-assignment5">
  <title>Assignment 5</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Find the set of points where the following functions are
        discontinuous. Are any of these sets open or closed?  (9)
        <ol>
          <li> 
            <me>
              f(x) = \left\{ \begin{matrix} xy \amp x \lt y \\ x + y
              \amp x \geq y \end{matrix} \right. 
            </me>
          </li>
          <li>
            <me>
              f(x,y,z) = |x + y + z|'
            </me>
          </li>
          <li> 
            <me>
              f(x) = \left\{ \begin{matrix} x^2 \amp x = 0 \\ x^2 + y
              \amp x > 0 \\ x^2 - y \amp x \lt 0 \end{matrix} \right.
            </me>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Prove that the following limits do not exist. (Assumed the
        functions are defined on maximum possible domains). (10)
        <ol>
          <li> 
            <me>
              \lim_{(x,y) \rightarrow (0,0)}  \frac{x^2+y^2}{x^2 -
              y^2}
            </me>
          </li>
          <li> 
            <me>
              \lim_{(x,y) \rightarrow (0,0)} \frac{x}{x^2 + y^2}
            </me>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider this function. (6)
        <me>
          f(x,y) = \frac{x^2 - y^2}{x-y}
        </me>
        This function is not defined on the line <m>x=y</m>. What
        values would you add to the function on that line to make the
        function continuous?
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Why are limits more difficult in several dimensions?  (4)
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate all the partial derivatives of the following
        functions. (12)
        <ol>
          <li>
            <m>f(x,y) = x^2 y^2 + (x+y)/e^x</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>f(x,y,z) = (xyz)^2</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>f(x,y,z) = \sin (x+y) - \cos (z-y)</m>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Draw a contour graph for the function <m>f(x,y) = \sin x \cos
        y</m>. Identify some points where both of the partial
        derivatives vanish. Describe the level curves close to these
        points? (8)
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider a differentiable function <m>f(x,y,z)</m>. Prove
        that if all the partial derivatives of <m>f</m> are <m>0</m>,
        then <m>f</m> must be constant. (6)
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Find the equations of the tangent planes to the following
        functions at the specified points. (12)
        <ol>
          <li>
            <m>f(x,y) = y \ln x</m> at <m>(1,4,0)</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>f(x,y) = x^2 - y^2</m> at <m>(2,-2,0)</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>f(x,y) = \frac{1}{x-y}</m> at <m>(3,2,1)</m>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Consider the function <m>f(x,y) = -(x^2 + y^2) + 4</m>. Where
        does the graph of this function intersect with the sphere or
        radius <m>4</m>?  Is the tangent plane at any of those points
        also tangent to the sphere? (8)
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        For the following function, calculate <m>\nabla f</m>, draw a
        countour diagram and label several of the gradient
        directions. (12)
        <ol>
          <li>
            <m>f(x,y) = \frac{1}{x^2 + y^2}</m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>f(x,y) = e^{x-y}</m>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Prove that if <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are functions of <m>x</m>
        and <m>y</m> then (4)
        <me> 
          \nabla (fg) = f \nabla g + g \nabla f
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        How can gradients help predict the courses of streams and
        rivers over a landscape? (4)
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>\omega(x,t) = f(x + at) + g(x - at)</m> for some
        constant <m>a \in \RR</m>, prove that the function
        <m>\omega</m> satisfies the wave equation. (4)
        <me>
          \frac{\del^2 \omega}{\del t^2} = a^2 \frac{\del^2
          \omega}{\del x^2}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>f(x,y) = g(x+y)</m>, prove the equavalence of partial
        derivatives. (6)
        <me>
          \frac{\del f}{\del x} = \frac{\del f}{\del y}
        </me>
        Are there other functions that satisfy this equivalence? (Give
        some thoughts and reasons, but a complete proof is not
        expected.)
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
</section>
